│ Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe issue manifests when transforming a select  │
│ instruction that has fast-math flags (nnan, ninf, nsz) into a sequence      │
│ involving llvm.maxnum.f32. The transformation is producing a more poisonous │
│ result than the original code.\n\nIn the test case with input %in = -inf    │
│ (-oo):\n- Original: fcmp nnan ogt %in, 0.0 returns false (since -inf is not │
│ > 0), so select returns 1.0\n- Transformed: llvm.maxnum.f32(%in, 0.0)       │
│ returns poison because %in = -inf and the intrinsic doesn't have ninf       │
│ flag\n\nThe problem is that the transformation in foldSelectIntoAddConstant │
│ creates a new select instruction and applies FastMathFlags that combine     │
│ both the original select and fadd flags, but this combined FMF may be too   │
│ aggressive for the intermediate select operation.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s   │
│ Log:\n\nThe log shows the transformation sequence:\n1. First,               │
│ foldSelectIntoAddConstant transforms the original select into: select(nn an │
│ ninf nsz i1 %cmp1, float %in, float 0.0)\n2. Then, this new select gets     │
│ transformed into llvm.maxnum.f32\n\nThe key issue is in the first           │
│ transformation where the new select instruction is created with             │
│ FastMathFlags that include ninf, but the select itself doesn't need or      │
│ benefit from the ninf flag. The ninf flag on the select causes the          │
│ subsequent maxnum transformation to inherit this flag incorrectly.\n\n3.    │
│ Root Cause Analysis:\n\nIn foldSelectIntoAddConstant function, lines        │
│ 3690-3697, the code computes NewFMF by intersecting and unioning the FMF    │
│ from both the select and fadd instructions. However, the ninf (no infinity) │
│ flag is not applicable to select instructions - it only applies to          │
│ floating-point arithmetic operations like fadd, fsub, etc.\n\nWhen this     │
│ inappropriate ninf flag is applied to the select instruction, it later      │
│ influences the maxnum intrinsic creation in the canonicalization at lines   │
│ 3925-3944. The maxnum intrinsic doesn't get the ninf flag set properly,     │
│ causing it to return poison for infinity inputs when it shouldn't.\n\nThe   │
│ fix is to ensure that only relevant fast-math flags are propagated to the   │
│ new select instruction. Specifically, ninf should not be propagated to      │
│ select instructions since they don't perform arithmetic that could produce  │
│ infinity.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe edit point is in the         │
│ foldSelectIntoAddConstant function where FastMathFlags are computed for the │
│ new instructions. We need to modify the FMF propagation to exclude ninf     │
│ from the select instruction, since select doesn't perform arithmetic        │
│ operations that could generate infinity.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nBy preventing │
│ the ninf flag from being incorrectly applied to the intermediate select     │
│ instruction, we ensure that the subsequent transformation to maxnum         │
│ intrinsic maintains the correct poison semantics. The select instruction    │
│ should only inherit flags that are meaningful for its operation (nnan and   │
│ nsz), while ninf should remain only on actual arithmetic operations like    │
│ fadd."})                                                                    │
